00:03:37.090 --> 00:03:40.480
Today's conference allows
us all to participate

00:03:40.480 --> 00:03:45.000
in an urgent conversation
about universities and slavery.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:47.650
Universities propel
our society forward

00:03:47.650 --> 00:03:50.440
through pioneering research
and the dissemination

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:51.880
of new knowledge.

00:03:51.880 --> 00:03:55.160
But they are also shaped
by their past, both

00:03:55.160 --> 00:04:00.070
the praiseworthy aspects and
the elements we prefer to avoid,

00:04:00.070 --> 00:04:04.030
Including those closely
bound up with slavery.

00:04:04.030 --> 00:04:06.490
Discussions about
universities and slavery

00:04:06.490 --> 00:04:09.240
began on individual campuses.

00:04:09.240 --> 00:04:13.300
In 2003, Brown University
President Ruth Simmons

00:04:13.300 --> 00:04:16.899
appointed a steering committee
on slavery and justice.

00:04:16.899 --> 00:04:21.519
And in 2007, Brown committed
to taking concrete steps

00:04:21.519 --> 00:04:26.170
to address and memorialize the
role of slavery in its history.

00:04:26.170 --> 00:04:28.780
In that same year,
Professors Sven Beckert

00:04:28.780 --> 00:04:32.860
began teaching an undergraduate
research seminar on the history

00:04:32.860 --> 00:04:35.470
of slavery here at Harvard.

00:04:35.470 --> 00:04:38.050
Meanwhile, descendants
of James Rollins,

00:04:38.050 --> 00:04:41.140
known as the Father of the
University of Missouri,

00:04:41.140 --> 00:04:45.850
established the James S. Rollins
Slavery Atonement Endowment

00:04:45.850 --> 00:04:48.760
to support the University
of Missouri's black studies

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:50.450
program.

00:04:50.450 --> 00:04:53.900
As the realization
spread that institutions

00:04:53.900 --> 00:04:57.830
of higher learning and
the institution of slavery

00:04:57.830 --> 00:05:00.440
shared an
interconnected history,

00:05:00.440 --> 00:05:03.290
many more schools
began investigating

00:05:03.290 --> 00:05:05.990
how slaves and
slavery had helped

00:05:05.990 --> 00:05:09.380
construct, in all
senses of that word,

00:05:09.380 --> 00:05:12.530
their own hallowed
halls of learning.

00:05:12.530 --> 00:05:16.820
Soon, universities began looking
beyond their own campus gates

00:05:16.820 --> 00:05:19.340
to learn more about
the role of slavery

00:05:19.340 --> 00:05:23.150
in the development of higher
education more broadly.

00:05:23.150 --> 00:05:26.240
Collective efforts have
included a landmark conference

00:05:26.240 --> 00:05:29.390
hosted by Emory
University in 2011,

00:05:29.390 --> 00:05:32.570
and the University Studying
Slavery Initiative, which

00:05:32.570 --> 00:05:36.590
began among schools in Virginia
and is now spread across state

00:05:36.590 --> 00:05:40.160
lines to include institutions
throughout the eastern half

00:05:40.160 --> 00:05:42.230
of the United States.

00:05:42.230 --> 00:05:43.790
The number of
universities coming

00:05:43.790 --> 00:05:47.420
to terms with this unsettling
part of their histories

00:05:47.420 --> 00:05:49.490
continues to grow.

00:05:49.490 --> 00:05:52.520
Students in the United
States and around the world

00:05:52.520 --> 00:05:54.980
are asking their
schools and colleges

00:05:54.980 --> 00:05:59.210
to take down statues of
slave-owning or slave-trading

00:05:59.210 --> 00:06:05.390
founders, rename buildings, and
redesign university insignia.

00:06:05.390 --> 00:06:09.920
Many of you in this audience
come from campuses now taking

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:12.920
seriously the
responsibility of learning

00:06:12.920 --> 00:06:17.690
what slavery has meant at
and for your own institution.

00:06:17.690 --> 00:06:22.670
Now it is time to make sure that
the larger public is included

00:06:22.670 --> 00:06:25.070
in this important conversation.

00:06:25.070 --> 00:06:27.920
So I am delighted at the
broad and diverse audience

00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:30.630
that we have
gathered here today.

00:06:30.630 --> 00:06:33.000
In order to move
forward, we must first

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:36.060
reckon with a complicated past.

00:06:36.060 --> 00:06:39.710
Through the impressive efforts
of many dedicated researchers

00:06:39.710 --> 00:06:43.230
we've been learning a great
deal about how slavery benefited

00:06:43.230 --> 00:06:46.020
universities financially
and through the labor

00:06:46.020 --> 00:06:48.240
of enslaved individuals.

00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:51.330
But we shouldn't
overlook how it also

00:06:51.330 --> 00:06:55.320
influence universities
intellectual development.

00:06:55.320 --> 00:06:59.820
Slavery shaped teaching methods,
curricula, and the evolution

00:06:59.820 --> 00:07:01.920
of entire disciplines.

00:07:01.920 --> 00:07:05.580
Today's conference will take
us deep into the consideration

00:07:05.580 --> 00:07:08.430
of these multifaceted
relationships.

00:07:08.430 --> 00:07:11.850
Let's begin by looking at
the cover of your conference

00:07:11.850 --> 00:07:14.090
program.

00:07:14.090 --> 00:07:16.560
So if you want to dig that out.

00:07:16.560 --> 00:07:20.040
The program cover
features a portrait

00:07:20.040 --> 00:07:24.150
of a man named Renty
who was born in Africa,

00:07:24.150 --> 00:07:27.780
kidnapped, and sold into
slavery in the United States

00:07:27.780 --> 00:07:30.990
in the first half
of the 19th century.

00:07:30.990 --> 00:07:34.230
This image was
taken in 1850, when

00:07:34.230 --> 00:07:38.610
Renty was a slave at Edgehill
Plantation near Columbia, South

00:07:38.610 --> 00:07:40.330
Carolina.

00:07:40.330 --> 00:07:45.520
Portraits were chiefly reserved
for the well-to-do in 1850.

00:07:45.520 --> 00:07:49.470
So who took this image, and why?

00:07:49.470 --> 00:07:51.660
It turns out, that
the portrait was

00:07:51.660 --> 00:07:56.070
taken for Louis Agassiz, a
Harvard professor and a world

00:07:56.070 --> 00:07:58.900
renowned scientist in his day.

00:07:58.900 --> 00:08:01.800
He was one of the inaugural
professors at the Lawrence

00:08:01.800 --> 00:08:05.070
Scientific School, the
precursor of today's

00:08:05.070 --> 00:08:08.070
John A. Paulson School of
Engineering and Applied

00:08:08.070 --> 00:08:10.530
Sciences here at Harvard.

00:08:10.530 --> 00:08:12.750
Some of you, in
fact, are watching

00:08:12.750 --> 00:08:16.230
from Agassiz House, that's
our overflow space, where

00:08:16.230 --> 00:08:19.260
we will all gather later
today for a reception

00:08:19.260 --> 00:08:20.820
after the conference.

00:08:20.820 --> 00:08:24.330
That building is named for
Elizabeth Cary Agassiz,

00:08:24.330 --> 00:08:27.810
herself a teacher, president
of Radcliffe College,

00:08:27.810 --> 00:08:29.760
and Louie's wife.

00:08:29.760 --> 00:08:33.780
Louis Agassiz was a proponent
of a scientific theory that

00:08:33.780 --> 00:08:36.240
was regarded as one of
the most cutting edge

00:08:36.240 --> 00:08:40.530
ideas of his day, the
Theory of Polygenesis.

00:08:40.530 --> 00:08:44.430
That theory denied that all
humans shared common ancestry,

00:08:44.430 --> 00:08:48.360
and instead posited that
different races were actually

00:08:48.360 --> 00:08:51.600
distinct and unequal species.

00:08:51.600 --> 00:08:55.710
In 1850, Agassiz traveled to
a South Carolina plantation

00:08:55.710 --> 00:08:58.530
to gather evidence
for polygenesis.

00:08:58.530 --> 00:09:02.220
He observed enslaved workers
there and long after his return

00:09:02.220 --> 00:09:04.320
to Cambridge, he
studied portraits

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:08.990
taken of five of the men
and two of the women.

00:09:08.990 --> 00:09:12.590
Agassiz classified and
cataloged those men and women

00:09:12.590 --> 00:09:14.780
by their physical
characteristics,

00:09:14.780 --> 00:09:18.650
in much the same way that he
had classified and cataloged

00:09:18.650 --> 00:09:22.070
species of animals
earlier in his career.

00:09:22.070 --> 00:09:25.530
The image of Renty that you see
on the cover of your program,

00:09:25.530 --> 00:09:29.630
and here on the screen,
is one of those images.

00:09:29.630 --> 00:09:33.890
To Agassiz, Renty was a specimen
to inform the Harvard teaching

00:09:33.890 --> 00:09:36.740
curriculum and to contribute
to the development

00:09:36.740 --> 00:09:39.710
of the academic disciplines
of comparative anatomy

00:09:39.710 --> 00:09:41.450
and anthropology.

00:09:41.450 --> 00:09:44.210
Renty's cataloged
biological characteristics

00:09:44.210 --> 00:09:46.280
were what interested Agassiz.

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:50.660
Today, it is Renty's personal
story that interests us.

00:09:50.660 --> 00:09:53.000
So what do we know
about that story?

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:55.370
The historical record
tells us that Renty was

00:09:55.370 --> 00:09:57.800
a member of the Congo Tribe.

00:09:57.800 --> 00:09:59.570
The historical record
tells us that he

00:09:59.570 --> 00:10:01.640
spent his days laboring.

00:10:01.640 --> 00:10:04.700
The historical record tells
us that he was a father.

00:10:04.700 --> 00:10:08.900
His daughter Delia also worked
on the Edgehill Plantation.

00:10:08.900 --> 00:10:12.590
Renty was surely much more
than either Agassiz's list

00:10:12.590 --> 00:10:15.050
of characteristics
or the bare facts

00:10:15.050 --> 00:10:18.530
revealed in the conventional
written historical record.

00:10:18.530 --> 00:10:20.840
Much of his personal
story remains

00:10:20.840 --> 00:10:24.080
unknown, or pieced
together by conjecture

00:10:24.080 --> 00:10:28.070
because so much has been erased
from that written record.

00:10:28.070 --> 00:10:29.990
But that does not
mean that we should

00:10:29.990 --> 00:10:32.960
stop trying to know more.

00:10:32.960 --> 00:10:35.180
We have in fact hosted
two seminars here

00:10:35.180 --> 00:10:37.250
at Radcliffe on
the Agassiz images.

00:10:37.250 --> 00:10:41.420
One in 2012 and another
in 2015, and you

00:10:41.420 --> 00:10:45.350
can read more about one campaign
to elevate Renty, literally,

00:10:45.350 --> 00:10:47.570
in my note in your program.

00:10:47.570 --> 00:10:49.730
For many years
the Agassiz images

00:10:49.730 --> 00:10:52.700
remained hidden in an
attic here at Harvard

00:10:52.700 --> 00:10:58.070
until Peabody Museum staff
rediscovered them in 1976.

00:10:58.070 --> 00:11:01.520
Similarly, the historical
tie between universities

00:11:01.520 --> 00:11:04.910
and slavery has remained
buried for years.

00:11:04.910 --> 00:11:07.610
But that relationship
could never fully

00:11:07.610 --> 00:11:11.780
disappear, any more than Renty's
photograph truly vanished--

00:11:11.780 --> 00:11:14.420
even when it was out of sight.

00:11:14.420 --> 00:11:16.730
Now we must comb
through the attics

00:11:16.730 --> 00:11:20.450
and open the disturbing drawers
of our universities past,

00:11:20.450 --> 00:11:22.640
no matter how difficult.

00:11:22.640 --> 00:11:24.650
As we do, I trust
that we will grow

00:11:24.650 --> 00:11:28.160
to appreciate more and more
how an image like Renty's has

00:11:28.160 --> 00:11:31.550
significance far beyond
the Edgehill Plantation

00:11:31.550 --> 00:11:35.330
in Columbia, South Carolina,
where he was enslaved.

00:11:35.330 --> 00:11:37.100
Thanks to our
distinguished speakers

00:11:37.100 --> 00:11:39.980
assembled here today and
through all of our efforts.

00:11:39.980 --> 00:11:43.370
We will and we must
continue to unearth history

00:11:43.370 --> 00:11:46.370
today and commit
to ensuring that it

00:11:46.370 --> 00:11:49.490
informs our work going forward.

00:11:49.490 --> 00:11:52.910
It is now my great pleasure
to welcome to the podium

00:11:52.910 --> 00:11:55.160
distinguished historian
and Harvard University

00:11:55.160 --> 00:11:56.960
President, Drew Gilpin Faust.

00:11:56.960 --> 00:12:00.404
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:07.790 --> 00:12:08.720
- Thank you.

00:12:08.720 --> 00:12:09.410
Thank you.

00:12:09.410 --> 00:12:13.160
I want to express my deepest
appreciation to Dean Lizabeth

00:12:13.160 --> 00:12:15.320
Cohen and her
Radcliffe colleagues

00:12:15.320 --> 00:12:17.900
for taking on my
request to sponsor

00:12:17.900 --> 00:12:22.430
this conference with such
enthusiasm and dedication.

00:12:22.430 --> 00:12:24.950
We are all very
much in their debt.

00:12:24.950 --> 00:12:28.970
I want to give special thanks to
faculty conference organizers,

00:12:28.970 --> 00:12:32.720
Evelyn Brooks Higginbotham,
Sven Beckert, and Dan Carpenter,

00:12:32.720 --> 00:12:35.360
for shaping such a rich program.

00:12:35.360 --> 00:12:37.340
And I also want to say
a special thank you

00:12:37.340 --> 00:12:40.550
to Megan Sniffin-Marinoff
and the staff of the Harvard

00:12:40.550 --> 00:12:45.200
University Archives for their
efforts to find our history.

00:12:45.200 --> 00:12:48.860
These are just in their early
stages, they will continue,

00:12:48.860 --> 00:12:52.430
but the exhibit that they
have already put together

00:12:52.430 --> 00:12:54.260
and the things they've
already uncovered

00:12:54.260 --> 00:12:57.740
are the beginning of a
very important trajectory

00:12:57.740 --> 00:13:01.640
of discovery that we
will be engaged in.

00:13:01.640 --> 00:13:03.950
Last April, members of
the Harvard community

00:13:03.950 --> 00:13:06.860
gathered together with
Congressman John Lewis

00:13:06.860 --> 00:13:10.820
to place a plaque at
Wadsworth House commemorating

00:13:10.820 --> 00:13:13.670
the lives of four
enslaved persons who had,

00:13:13.670 --> 00:13:16.520
during the 18th
century, worked there

00:13:16.520 --> 00:13:20.030
in the households of
two Harvard presidents.

00:13:20.030 --> 00:13:24.320
This effort was intended to
be one milestone in a broader

00:13:24.320 --> 00:13:27.410
exploration of an
aspect of Harvard's past

00:13:27.410 --> 00:13:30.710
that has been rarely
acknowledged and poorly

00:13:30.710 --> 00:13:32.510
understood.

00:13:32.510 --> 00:13:36.920
Harvard was directly complicit
in slavery from the college's

00:13:36.920 --> 00:13:40.880
earliest days in
the 17th century,

00:13:40.880 --> 00:13:46.820
until the system of bondage
ended in Massachusetts in 1783.

00:13:46.820 --> 00:13:50.150
Then, through financial and
other ties with the slave

00:13:50.150 --> 00:13:54.530
South, Harvard continued to
be involved with slavery up

00:13:54.530 --> 00:13:57.710
until the time of emancipation.

00:13:57.710 --> 00:14:02.120
This history and its legacy
have shaped our institution

00:14:02.120 --> 00:14:05.840
in ways we have yet
to fully understand.

00:14:05.840 --> 00:14:08.000
Today's conference
is intended to help

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:11.450
us explore parts of
the past that have

00:14:11.450 --> 00:14:14.600
remained all but invisible.

00:14:14.600 --> 00:14:17.840
To acknowledge those
realities is essential

00:14:17.840 --> 00:14:21.320
if we are to undermine the
legacies of race and slavery

00:14:21.320 --> 00:14:24.530
that continue to
divide our nation.

00:14:24.530 --> 00:14:26.750
And if we are to
commit ourselves

00:14:26.750 --> 00:14:29.450
to building a better future.

00:14:29.450 --> 00:14:33.980
Slavery of course, is part,
not just of Harvard's history,

00:14:33.980 --> 00:14:37.610
but embedded in the past of
universities across the United

00:14:37.610 --> 00:14:42.260
States and in the world
beyond our national borders.

00:14:42.260 --> 00:14:46.610
Today we will also examine
this broader context,

00:14:46.610 --> 00:14:50.600
investigating historical
similarities and differences,

00:14:50.600 --> 00:14:54.170
as well as the range
of contemporary efforts

00:14:54.170 --> 00:14:58.400
to confront slavery's
distressing legacies.

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:03.050
So we look at both past and
present today in the firm

00:15:03.050 --> 00:15:06.950
belief that only by coming
to terms with history can

00:15:06.950 --> 00:15:11.670
we free ourselves to
create a more just world.

00:15:11.670 --> 00:15:16.280
Thank you for joining
us in that enterprise.

00:15:16.280 --> 00:15:19.460
As our keynote
speaker, we are honored

00:15:19.460 --> 00:15:24.260
to have the ideal person
to lead us in that work.

00:15:24.260 --> 00:15:26.750
His many honors
and accomplishments

00:15:26.750 --> 00:15:29.640
are detailed in your program.

00:15:29.640 --> 00:15:32.990
Please join me in
welcoming Ta-Nehisi Coates.

00:15:32.990 --> 00:15:36.490
